description.text:
A tray to mount your Sanguinololu to the base of your Prusa with cover that can hold a 40x40mm fan.
I have printed it myself in black PLA with 30% interior fill. The studs to mount the PCB should not get to hot wile printing (use cooling or get your towers setting right) or they need some filing/ sending after the print.
The one I've printed fits perfectly. You can mount it under the printbed or outside the frame.

• print

  • install fan: if you want a fan glue it under the cover at the marked area. If you want to use screws you can drill the holes for them through the cover and use 4 x m4 to mount the fan. Glueing will give a nicer cover.

  • decide where you want the tray

  • glue the hook under the tray so that the hook is over the rod parallel to the printbed and the lip resting on the rod that is attached to the z-axis

  • mount the Sanguinololu on the bottom with the self tapping screws to secure top and bottom (you can also use m3 nut and bolt to secure top and bottom but you have to drill the holes through the top)

  • put one or two cable ties through the holes of the lip to secure the tray

  • share your print ;-)

description.text: Revised the filament duct to fit between the factory extruder fans. Also reworked the geometry where the tube interfaces with the fan mount. It is up to you to check for fitment. It should also be noted that a number of the extruder drive blocks out there have geometry such that the flow from this tube to anywhere near the filament will be blocked. This loot chest from Borderlands is based on the original design from the first game and I modelled it directly from the "Ultimate Loot Chest" Edition of the collectible for Borderlands 2 (it's confusing that the design is from Borderlands 1) so it's visually very accurate. I scaled it to be ~15 cm along the width and ~5 cm high.
The chest itself is hinged so the lid is free to open and close! The lock mechanism itself is only a dummy, so I made the chest with slots for neodymium magnets to keep the lid closed.
The Body has a small recess at the back removed with slots so electronics can be implemented, i.e. adding lights to the panels; this can be backed with a thin sheet of plastic to hide the electronics. The panels are also windowless with the intent of backing it with frosted plastic so lights can disperse evenly.
This is my first model with functional features so I can't guarantee it works so any tips, advice and feedback to improve the model is greatly appreciated. 
Future ideas include making a pneumatic lift that raises the platform, just like in the game but that is a bit beyond me, but someday I'll give it a try.

description.text:
In 2013 i needed an eye catcher for several Maker Faires. So i decided to hack a game called Loopin' Louie ( in most parts of Europe Looping Louie). I added some 3D printed parts to it and connected another Toy called "Mind Flex" mind controller. With this additional parts and some servos the player is able to "control" the game with his brain. A more lightweight version is using a servo and an ( 3 pin) ultra sonic sensor. When Louie hits the programmed height of the ultrasonic sensor, the "Autopilot" mechanism is triggered and the players seesaw clicks to the top. Afterwards the notch is tightened again and the "Autopilot" waits that Louie comes around the next time. Print all needed parts, drill holes to the game's seesaw(s) and screw it together like on the pictures. The video shows the Game at Maker Faire Kerkrade (NL) in 2013. description.text: This thing was made with Tinkercad. Edit it online https://www.tinkercad.com/things/j8cHZ3QULLG

This is a parametric OpenSCAD for generating round knitting looms, that can be used for making hats, socks, etc. You can see pictures of these on google, e.g., http://www.google.com/search?hl=en&q=round+knitting+loom Because it is parametric, you can use this to create an arbitrary density of pins: make any "gauge" or size of knitting device you like. I created this mainly to learn how to use OpenSCAD and because I think knitting is theoretically interesting (although I don't have the patience to do it)

The object is generated using the roundLoom() function. The model in the STL file was generated by calling the function with the following arguments. roundLoom(frameHeight = 5, frameDiam = 40, frameWidth = 5, //set the frame geometry
nPins=6, pinHeight=10, pinDiam=4, //set the pin geometry
addKnobs=true, knobDiam = 6, // set the knob on the top of each pin
addSide=true, sideHeight=8); // add a pin on the side? the frame parameters describe the base frame, and the pin variables determine the dimensions of the pins. The frame diameter, frameDiam determines the center of each of the pins. The boolean variable addKnobs controls whether to add little knobs on to the tops of the pins, and boolean variable addSide controls whether to add a pin on the side of the frame (you can see this in some of the google images online.)

Got tired of carrying my meds in their plates around everytime when I left home for a few days and our pharmacies only sold those huge dispensers with like 4 slots / day which I (luckily) don't have a need for. So: ^-^
One week pill dispenser with super easy construction fitted into smallest space possible. I considered one of those 8 slot rotating ones with one "blank" slot to close the lid first, but found that this way I managed to bring the size down more and well, it works so...

description.text: Small container de 29 x 40 mm.

I designed this to hold my iPhone4 with a Speck Candyshell case in the car when using it as a GPS. I wanted a mount that could work in any car, so the lighter socket was an obvious choice. It also eliminates the need to carry a separate charger and cable. It holds the phone quite firmly without blocking access to any of the connectors, switches or buttons on the phone.
All of the SCAD files are included, so it shouldn't be hard to adapt the design to different phone cases, or for no case at all.
NOTE: The design calls for a switching regulator available from Gravitech. While this part is a pin-compatible replacement for the LM7805, it is a switching regulator and this is very important. The iPhone can draw up to 1A, and the 7805 linear regulator would be dissipating close to 8W, so it is important to use a switching regulator.

• Print the 3 pieces of the mount
  • Cut off the outlet portion of the dual outlet adapter right where it ceases to be round. I saved the dual outlets and added some wires to use on my workbench with a bench power supply.
  • Extend the wires on the plug by about 6in/150mm.
  • Solvent weld the extension piece into the lighter plug with the wires through the middle.
  • Solvent weld the extension piece into the mount base. You might want to experiment with the orientation in your car at this point to take best advantage of the tilt feature.
  • Install the circuitry in the mount base. Space is tight so I decided to not use a circuit board. The circular depression in the base is for the inductor on the Gravitech switching regulator
  • Mount the base assembly to the phone mount using 3 M3x16mm screws.

description.text: Okay, this is not quite done, but I thought I'd throw it out there anyway. This version is less prone to cracking. Instead of a washer and nut, there is an M6 tapped hole in a piece of aluminum. But best of all, two can be bolted together to form a dual head extruder. Yes, you can have one or two of the same extruder! I'm working on a mount for this right now. See my YouTube videos of previous versions for theory of operation (http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=HMjVrmLJvIU) and how quickly the filament can be changed (http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=z_isuzpvjBc) Subversion http://svn.makerbot.com/users/charles/paxtruder/

comments.text: What a great design! When can I buy a 'kit' of the plexiglas pieces to build one up using parts from a torn down mk4 extruder?  I've tried 3 builds to get consistant extruding from 2 different plastruder mk4s with no luck. Sure would like to try your version out.

comments.text: I'm assuming you ar eusing Delrin for it's low co-efficient of friction... so what about using PTFE ( ie Teflon ) as used in the thermal barrier, which has an even lower co-efficient, and you are then reducing the number of different materials that need sourcing.

description.text: This is based on the stylized Fleur-de-lis design found in the letter "O" in the graphic title for the "The Originals" TV series, intended to be used as a pendant (current or similar scale) or earrings (I suggest scaling it down as close to 20mm as your printer can handle). The full size (50mm tall) design has a 3mm diameter hole in the top petal (see picture). There's also a 50x36mm version that has a second, smaller hole in the bottom "teardrop" for attaching a loop and hanging beads/crystals/etc. ...it's not anything I'm in to, but hey, my wife is and I've got to justify my printing expenses somehow, right? ;)

Notes: As seen in the pics, I've printed this in a variety of colors and scaled in my slicer (Simplify3D, but any should work) to different sizes, all with equal success. The difficult part is getting the pointy end of the large central petal to stay sharp; I suggest using that part of the model to judge what settings are "best" for your particular printer. Most (all?) of these were printed with 4 to 6 top layers, 2 perimeters, and range is size from 20mm up to 70mm (which, granted, is crazy-big).

description.text:
I really liked the Velociraptor Business card by Cleven but i have no need for a business card, so i "un-business-carded" it, extruded it and made it much bigger so it assembles effortlessly and looks cool on your desk.
It is ca. 23cm in length and 11.5cm in height. The head parts (The parts with the teeth) produced a couple of misprints on an Ultimaker 2, maybe it is a good idea to print them separately. If you want to scale it just scale the STL file, it should still be intermateable afterwards. I included the vector forms (Inkscape SVG file) which i extracted and corrected from the .dxf the original author included. To extrude the SVG in OpenSCAD (Which can only import STL or DXF files) i used this excellent Inkscape extension: Inkscape OpenSCAD DXF Export Also check out this longer tail for balance from galiettd!
